\section{Block separator}
\label{sec:block-sep}

Multiple runs without code changes are appended to the same
commit message, separated by a line of three dashes surrounded
by blank lines (see \cref{gitrepo}).
This separator is safe to split on because the section markers
within a run block ([[--- I/O ---]], [[--- exception ---]])
always have additional text after the dashes.

We define it here rather than in the CLI module because both
the commit functions and the ProgSnap2 exporter need it.

<<commits constants>>=
BLOCK_SEP = "\n\n---\n\n"
@


\section{Listing commits}

We list commits in chronological order (oldest first) because
that matches the natural playback direction: the student starts
writing code and we watch their progress forward in time.

<<commits functions>>=
def get_commits(repo):
    """Return a list of commits in chronological order.

    Each entry is a dict with ``hash``, ``subject``, and
    ``date`` keys.
    """
    result = repo.git(
        "log", "--format=%H\t%s\t%aI", "--reverse"
    )
    if result.returncode != 0:
        return []
    commits = []
    for line in result.stdout.strip().split("\n"):
        if not line:
            continue
        parts = line.split("\t", 2)
        if len(parts) == 3:
            commits.append({
                "hash": parts[0],
                "subject": parts[1],
                "date": parts[2],
            })
    return commits
@

<<commits test functions>>=
def test_get_commits_returns_chronological(workdir):
    from learnlog.commits import get_commits
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)
    t1 = datetime.datetime(2026, 1, 1, 10, 0)
    repo.begin_run("hello.py", [], t1)
    (workdir / "hello.py").write_text('print("v2")\n')
    t2 = datetime.datetime(2026, 1, 1, 10, 5)
    repo.begin_run("hello.py", [], t2)
    commits = get_commits(repo)
    assert len(commits) >= 2
    assert commits[0]["hash"] != commits[-1]["hash"]

def test_get_commits_has_required_keys(workdir):
    from learnlog.commits import get_commits
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)
    commits = get_commits(repo)
    assert len(commits) >= 1
    for key in ("hash", "subject", "date"):
        assert key in commits[0]
